INSERT INTO flashcards (course_id, question_text, answer_text, difficulty, order_index) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the definition of clinical governance according to Scally and Donaldson?', 'Scally and Donaldson (1998) defined clinical governance as: ''A framework through which NHS organisations are accountable for continuously improving the quality of their services and safeguarding high standards of care by creating an environment in which excellence in clinical care will flourish.'' It represents the systematic approach to quality assurance in healthcare and holds organisations (not just individuals) responsible for care quality and safety.', 1, 26),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What are the seven pillars of clinical governance?', 'The seven pillars are: (1) Clinical effectiveness — evidence-based care that achieves outcomes. (2) Risk management — identifying and managing clinical and organisational risks. (3) Patient experience — involving patients and improving satisfaction. (4) Communication — effective information sharing within the team and with patients. (5) Resource effectiveness — efficient use of people, finances, and technology. (6) Strategic effectiveness — aligning governance with organisational strategy. (7) Learning effectiveness — using learning from incidents, complaints, and audits to improve.', 2, 27),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the clinical audit cycle and what is its purpose?', 'The clinical audit cycle has five stages: (1) Select a topic and set standards (based on evidence/guidelines). (2) Collect data against the standards. (3) Analyse and compare data to standards. (4) Implement changes (education, protocol updates, pathway changes). (5) Re-audit to confirm improvement (closing the loop). The purpose is to systematically assess whether care meets defined standards and to drive continuous quality improvement. Audits are not investigations of individuals — they are assessments of systems and processes.', 2, 28),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is evidence-based practice and why is it important in clinical governance?', 'Evidence-based practice (EBP) is the integration of the best available research evidence with clinical expertise and patient values to guide clinical decision-making. It is important because it ensures that care is based on what has been proven to work (or not to work) rather than tradition or habit. EBP underpins clinical effectiveness — one of the seven pillars of governance. It requires clinicians to appraise evidence, access guidelines, and apply research findings to their individual patient contexts.', 2, 29),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the hierarchy of evidence in evidence-based practice?', 'From highest to lowest quality: (1) Systematic reviews and meta-analyses of RCTs. (2) Randomised Controlled Trials (RCTs) — gold standard for intervention research. (3) Cohort studies (prospective or retrospective observational). (4) Case-control studies. (5) Cross-sectional surveys. (6) Case series and case reports. (7) Expert opinion and clinical experience. Higher levels of evidence carry more certainty; lower levels are more susceptible to bias. NICE uses the GRADE framework to rate the quality of evidence in its guidelines.', 2, 30),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the legal status of NICE guidelines and how should they be used?', 'NICE guidelines are not legally binding but represent best available evidence and are regarded as best practice. They are produced by NICE (National Institute for Health and Care Excellence) following systematic review of evidence. In England, NHS organisations have a duty to have regard to NICE guidance. Deviation must be clinically justified and documented. In negligence cases, failure to follow NICE guidelines without justification can be used as evidence of substandard care. NICE guidelines should be implemented at local level through policies, protocols, and pathways.', 2, 31),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What are the categories of patient safety incidents?', 'Patient safety incidents are classified by degree of harm: No harm — incident occurred but caused no harm (or was prevented before reaching the patient — near miss). Low harm — minor, short-term harm requiring minimal treatment. Moderate harm — moderate, longer-term harm requiring additional treatment or extended stay. Severe harm — permanent or long-term significant harm. Death — directly caused by incident. Near miss: incident that did not reach the patient. All incidents should be reported via the local system (e.g. Datix) regardless of harm level.', 2, 32),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the statutory duty of candour for organisations?', 'The statutory duty of candour (Regulation 20 of the Health and Social Care Act 2008 Regulations 2014) requires NHS and registered care providers to be open and transparent with patients when moderate, severe harm or death has occurred as a result of a notifiable safety incident. The organisation must: notify the patient/family in person as soon as reasonably practicable, provide a written apology, investigate, and inform the patient of the results of the investigation. This is distinct from the professional duty of candour in the NMC Code (which applies to individual practitioners).', 3, 33),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the Serious Incident (SI) investigation process?', 'A Serious Incident (SI) is a patient safety event that causes severe harm, death, or significant learning. When an SI is declared: the responsible organisation notifies NHS England/ICB. An investigation team is appointed. Root cause analysis (RCA) is conducted. A report with an action plan is produced within 60 days. The report is shared with the patient/family (duty of candour). Learning is shared across the organisation and system. The SI framework is overseen by NHS England''s Patient Safety Incident Response Framework (PSIRF).', 3, 34),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is root cause analysis (RCA) and what methods are used?', 'RCA is a structured approach to identifying the fundamental causes of a patient safety incident rather than just the immediate trigger. Common methods: Fishbone diagram (Ishikawa) — visually categorises contributing factors (people, process, environment, equipment, materials, management). 5 Whys — repeatedly asking ''why'' to trace back from the outcome to the root cause. Timeline analysis — chronological reconstruction of events. RCA aims to identify system failures and latent conditions rather than blame individuals. Actions target the root causes to prevent recurrence.', 3, 35),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the LeDeR programme and what is its significance?', 'LeDeR (Learning from Lives and Deaths — People with a Learning Disability and Autistic People) is an NHS programme that reviews the deaths of people with learning disabilities and autism to identify potentially avoidable deaths and system failures. It has highlighted that people with learning disabilities die on average 20–25 years earlier than the general population, often from avoidable conditions. Key themes from LeDeR reports: diagnostic overshadowing, poor adjustments for disability, communication failures, and lack of reasonable adjustments. Every death of a person with learning disabilities triggers a review.', 2, 36),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What are the CQC''s five inspection domains?', 'The Care Quality Commission (CQC) inspects health and social care providers against five domains: (1) Safe — people are protected from avoidable harm. (2) Effective — care achieves good outcomes. (3) Caring — staff treat people with compassion and dignity. (4) Responsive — services are organised to meet individual needs. (5) Well-led — leadership, management, and governance support good care culture. Each domain is rated: Outstanding, Good, Requires Improvement, or Inadequate. Overall ratings are published on the CQC website.', 1, 37),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the CQC ratings system and what happens when a service is rated Inadequate?', 'CQC rates services in each of the five domains as: Outstanding, Good, Requires Improvement, or Inadequate. Overall rating is determined by the CQC''s aggregation approach, with ''Safe'' carrying particular weight. Inadequate rating: the CQC may take enforcement action, impose conditions, issue requirement or warning notices, cancel registration, or prosecute. Inadequate services are placed in ''Special Measures'' — subject to more frequent inspection and monitored improvement trajectory. Services must produce an action plan.', 3, 38),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What are the CQC''s Fundamental Standards?', 'CQC Fundamental Standards (Health and Social Care Act 2008 Regulated Activities Regulations 2014) are the minimum standards below which care must never fall. They include: person-centred care, dignity and respect, consent, safe care and treatment, safeguarding, meeting nutritional needs, premises and equipment, complaints handling, good governance, staffing, fit and proper persons, duty of candour, and display of ratings. Breaching fundamental standards can result in prosecution without prior warning. They represent the legal floor for care quality.', 2, 39),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'How does whistleblowing relate to clinical governance?', 'Whistleblowing (making a protected disclosure under the Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998) is the reporting of concerns about patient safety, wrongdoing, illegal acts, or misuse of public funds. It is an essential element of clinical governance — the Francis Inquiry (2013) highlighted that staff at Mid Staffordshire NHS Foundation Trust failed to raise concerns about poor care. NHS organisations must have a Freedom to Speak Up (FTSU) Guardian and a culture that supports raising concerns without fear of reprisal. Whistleblowers are legally protected if acting in good faith.', 2, 40),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is a clinical risk register and how is it used?', 'A clinical risk register is a formal document that records identified clinical risks within an organisation or clinical area, including: the risk description, likelihood and consequence scores (RAG rating), current controls, residual risk, owner, and review date. Risks are reviewed regularly by governance committees. Risks that cannot be adequately controlled are escalated to the board. Risk registers support proactive risk management — identifying and mitigating risks before incidents occur. They are a key tool in the risk management pillar of clinical governance.', 2, 41),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the NHS Friends and Family Test and how does it inform governance?', 'The NHS Friends and Family Test (FFT) is a patient experience feedback mechanism used across NHS services. Patients are asked: ''Overall, how was your experience of our service?'' (rated 1–5 or Very Good to Very Poor) and encouraged to give free-text comments. Results are published monthly at organisational and ward level, allowing benchmarking and public accountability. FFT data informs the ''Patient Experience'' pillar of governance and the CQC ''Caring'' domain. High negative response rates trigger quality improvement action.', 1, 42),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What are mortality and morbidity (M&M) reviews and their governance function?', 'M&M reviews are regular multidisciplinary meetings (usually monthly) that examine cases involving unexpected deaths or significant complications. They review whether care was of an expected standard, whether there were avoidable contributing factors, and what learning can be drawn. M&M reviews are a governance mechanism for continuous improvement — they feed into the organisation''s learning culture and can identify themes for audit or policy change. They are non-punitive and conducted under legal privilege in some trusts. Attendance of all clinical grades is important.', 2, 43),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'How is benchmarking used in clinical governance?', 'Benchmarking compares an organisation''s performance against comparable organisations or national standards to identify areas of strength and improvement. Sources of benchmarking data: NHS England national data, CQC inspection reports, NHSI metrics, mortality indices (HSMR, SHMI), Commissioning for Quality and Innovation (CQUIN) targets, and clinical audit networks. Benchmarking helps organisations identify outliers, understand their relative performance, and prioritise governance activity. External benchmarking drives accountability and transparency.', 2, 44),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the role of governance committees in NHS trusts and care organisations?', 'Governance committees provide the organisational structure for clinical governance. Typical structure: Ward/departmental level — local governance meetings reviewing incidents, audits, complaints. Divisional level — aggregating data and overseeing improvement. Trust/Board level — Quality and Safety Committee or equivalent reporting to the Board. The Board is ultimately responsible for governance. Committees review: serious incidents, complaint themes, audit results, risk register, mortality data, CQC actions, and staff wellbeing metrics. Minutes must be kept and actions tracked.', 3, 45),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'Why is staff wellbeing a clinical governance priority?', 'Evidence shows a strong association between staff wellbeing (psychological safety, job satisfaction, manageable workload) and patient safety and experience outcomes. NHS organisations with higher staff engagement have lower mortality rates and fewer adverse events (NHS Staff Survey data). Staff wellbeing is explicitly addressed in the CQC''s ''Well-Led'' domain. Burnout, moral injury, and poor working conditions increase error rates and turnover. Governance frameworks must include workforce wellbeing metrics, staff survey action plans, and occupational health provision.', 2, 46),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is research governance and how does it relate to clinical governance?', 'Research governance is the framework that ensures research conducted in healthcare organisations meets ethical, scientific, and legal standards. Key components: ethical approval (NHS Research Ethics Committee), approval under the NHS Research Governance Framework, Research and Development (R&D) office oversight, Good Clinical Practice (GCP) training for researchers, informed consent, data protection compliance, and monitoring of research adverse events. It sits alongside clinical governance as a quality framework specific to research. The Health Research Authority (HRA) oversees research governance in England.', 3, 47),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'How does information governance (IG) relate to clinical governance?', 'Information governance is the framework ensuring that health and social care organisations collect, store, use, and share data in a secure, lawful, and appropriate manner. Key elements: compliance with UK GDPR and the Data Protection Act 2018, Caldicott Principles (for patient information use), NHS Digital Data Security and Protection (DSP) Toolkit compliance, information security policies, and data breach management. Information governance is integral to clinical governance — poor IG (e.g. data breaches) can harm patients and undermine trust. All staff must complete annual IG training.', 2, 48),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'How is clinical governance integrated into daily practice?', 'Clinical governance is not only a committee function — it is everyone''s responsibility. Daily integration includes: completing incident reports promptly, participating in clinical supervision and appraisal, engaging with audit data and change projects, attending M&M and team governance meetings, following evidence-based protocols, raising concerns (Freedom to Speak Up), maintaining documentation standards, taking part in multidisciplinary team reviews, and applying learning from feedback and complaints. Governance is embedded in safe, effective, compassionate daily practice.', 1, 49),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What was the significance of the Francis Inquiry for clinical governance in the NHS?', 'The Francis Inquiry (2013) investigated the failures at Mid Staffordshire NHS Foundation Trust where hundreds of patients suffered and died due to poor care and a culture that prioritised financial targets over patient safety. Key findings: normalisation of poor practice, staff unable to raise concerns without fear, board failure to act on governance data, and systemic cultural problems. The inquiry led to: introduction of the statutory duty of candour, Freedom to Speak Up Guardian programme, CQC Fundamental Standards, and renewed emphasis on patient safety culture in NHS governance.', 2, 50)
INSERT INTO quiz_questions (course_id, question_text, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_option, explanation) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'How many pillars does the clinical governance framework have?', 'Four', 'Five', 'Seven', 'Ten', 'C', 'The clinical governance framework has seven pillars: clinical effectiveness, risk management, patient experience, communication, resource effectiveness, strategic effectiveness, and learning effectiveness. These pillars provide a comprehensive framework for organisations to continuously improve the quality and safety of care.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the correct order of the clinical audit cycle?', 'Set standards → Collect data → Implement change → Re-audit → Select topic', 'Select topic → Set standards → Collect data → Analyse results → Implement change → Re-audit', 'Collect data → Set standards → Analyse → Report → Close', 'Implement change → Collect data → Set standards → Re-audit', 'B', 'The clinical audit cycle follows this order: (1) Select a topic, (2) Set standards based on evidence or guidelines, (3) Collect data, (4) Analyse and compare results against standards, (5) Implement changes where gaps are identified, (6) Re-audit to confirm improvement. The final stage closes the loop and confirms whether the changes have been effective.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the legal status of NICE guidelines in England?', 'They are legally binding on all NHS providers', 'They are aspirational targets with no regulatory standing', 'They represent best practice and NHS organisations have a duty to have regard to them; deviation must be clinically justified', 'They apply only to primary care settings', 'C', 'NICE guidelines are not legally binding but represent best available evidence. NHS organisations in England have a duty to have regard to NICE guidance. Clinicians can deviate from guidelines but must document their clinical justification. In negligence cases, unexplained deviation from NICE guidance may be considered substandard care.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'Under the statutory duty of candour (Regulation 20), when must an organisation notify a patient that a safety incident has occurred?', 'Within 28 days of the incident becoming known', 'Only after the investigation is complete', 'As soon as reasonably practicable after a notifiable safety incident causing moderate, severe harm, or death', 'Only if the patient requests information about their care', 'C', 'The statutory duty of candour (Regulation 20 of the Health and Social Care Act 2008 Regulations 2014) requires that patients are notified as soon as reasonably practicable when a notifiable patient safety incident has occurred that resulted in moderate harm, severe harm, or death. A written apology must also be provided. Notification must not be delayed until after the investigation concludes.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'When conducting root cause analysis using the 5 Whys method, what is the purpose of continuing to ask ''why''?', 'To assign individual blame for the incident', 'To trace back from the immediate cause to the fundamental system or process failure', 'To identify the financial cost of the incident', 'To determine legal liability for the event', 'B', 'The 5 Whys technique repeatedly asks ''why'' to move beyond the immediate trigger of an incident to the root or fundamental cause — which is typically a system, process, or cultural failure rather than individual error. It helps design interventions that prevent recurrence by fixing the underlying problem rather than just addressing the surface event.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'Which of the CQC''s five inspection domains is specifically concerned with leadership, governance, and organisational culture?', 'Safe', 'Effective', 'Responsive', 'Well-Led', 'D', 'The ''Well-Led'' domain assesses leadership, management, and governance arrangements, including: how the organisation uses information to drive improvement, the organisational culture, staff wellbeing, and whether there is a credible strategy for quality improvement. It is one of the five CQC domains alongside Safe, Effective, Caring, and Responsive.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'A nurse witnesses a colleague administering a drug without checking the patient''s allergy status, but the patient was not harmed. What clinical governance action is most appropriate?', 'Ignore the incident as no harm occurred', 'Report the incident via the organisation''s incident reporting system (e.g. Datix), as near misses are valuable learning opportunities', 'Confront the colleague publicly at the next team meeting', 'Submit a direct referral to the CQC', 'B', 'Near misses (incidents that could have caused harm but did not) are valuable patient safety learning opportunities and must be reported via the local incident reporting system. Analysis of near misses reveals system vulnerabilities before harm occurs. The NMC Code also requires nurses to raise concerns about unsafe practice. Internal reporting via Datix or equivalent is the first step.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What does the Friends and Family Test (FFT) ask patients?', 'Would you like to see more staff on the ward?', 'How would you rate your overall experience of this service?', 'Do you understand your treatment plan?', 'Would you complain if given the opportunity?', 'B', 'The NHS Friends and Family Test asks patients to rate their overall experience of the service (on a scale from Very Good to Very Poor) and optionally provide free-text feedback. Results are published monthly and provide patient experience data for governance purposes, enabling benchmarking and public accountability at service level.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the primary purpose of a clinical risk register?', 'To record every patient safety incident that has occurred', 'To proactively document identified risks, their likelihood and consequence, current controls, and residual risk to enable management before incidents occur', 'To provide evidence of compliance for CQC inspections only', 'To record individual staff members'' performance concerns', 'B', 'A clinical risk register is a proactive governance tool that identifies and documents risks in a clinical area before they cause harm. Each risk is scored for likelihood and consequence (RAG rated), current mitigations are recorded, and residual risk is assessed. The register is reviewed regularly at governance meetings and escalated to the board for unmanageable risks. It supports the risk management pillar of clinical governance.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'Which level of evidence is considered the most reliable for informing clinical practice guidelines?', 'Case reports and case series', 'Expert opinion from experienced clinicians', 'Systematic reviews and meta-analyses of randomised controlled trials', 'Cross-sectional surveys', 'C', 'Systematic reviews and meta-analyses of randomised controlled trials (RCTs) represent the highest level of evidence in the hierarchy, as they systematically pool the results of multiple high-quality studies to provide the most reliable estimate of the effectiveness of an intervention. NICE and other guideline developers prioritise this level of evidence when available.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What was the primary lesson for clinical governance from the Francis Inquiry into Mid Staffordshire NHS Foundation Trust?', 'That only senior managers are responsible for governance failures', 'That clinical governance committees alone can ensure safe care', 'That a culture of prioritising financial targets over patient safety, combined with a failure to raise and act on concerns, enabled systematic care failures', 'That external regulation by CQC is sufficient to prevent poor care', 'C', 'The Francis Inquiry identified that a toxic organisational culture — which normalised poor practice, suppressed staff from raising concerns, and prioritised performance targets over patient welfare — was the fundamental cause of the failures at Mid Staffordshire. It resulted in major reforms including statutory duty of candour, Freedom to Speak Up Guardians, and a renewed focus on governance culture rather than just committee processes.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the LeDeR programme?', 'A system for reviewing serious incidents in acute NHS trusts', 'A review programme for deaths of people with learning disabilities and autistic people, identifying avoidable deaths and system failures', 'A tool for learning from medication errors', 'An NHSI programme for mortality reduction across NHS trusts', 'B', 'LeDeR (Learning from Lives and Deaths — People with a Learning Disability and Autistic People) is an NHS review programme that examines every death of a person with a learning disability or autism to identify avoidable factors and system failures. LeDeR reports have highlighted premature mortality, diagnostic overshadowing, communication failures, and lack of reasonable adjustments as recurring themes requiring governance action.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the role of the Freedom to Speak Up (FTSU) Guardian in an NHS organisation?', 'To investigate serious incidents on behalf of the board', 'To provide confidential, independent support to staff wishing to raise concerns about patient safety or organisational culture', 'To manage complaints from patients and the public', 'To oversee CQC compliance and inspection readiness', 'B', 'FTSU Guardians provide a confidential, independent point of contact for staff to raise concerns about patient safety, bullying, or organisational culture issues without fear of reprisal. They were established following the Francis Inquiry recommendations. All NHS trusts and some independent providers are required to have a FTSU Guardian. Staff raising concerns in good faith are protected under the Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'Which framework replaced the previous Serious Incident Framework for managing patient safety incidents in the NHS?', 'Never Events Framework', 'Patient Safety Incident Response Framework (PSIRF)', 'Root Cause Analysis National Framework', 'NHS Serious Harm Reporting System', 'B', 'The Patient Safety Incident Response Framework (PSIRF, 2022) replaced the previous NHS Serious Incident Framework. PSIRF introduces a proportionate, learning-focused approach to investigating patient safety incidents. It emphasises learning system improvement over blame, requires Patient Safety Incident Response Plans (PSIRPs) from organisations, and uses a range of investigation methods appropriate to the nature and complexity of the incident.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000030', 'What is the Data Security and Protection (DSP) Toolkit and why is it relevant to clinical governance?', 'A toolkit for securing medication rooms and clinical areas', 'An NHS assessment framework that organisations must complete annually to demonstrate compliance with data security and information governance requirements', 'A CQC inspection tool for assessing record-keeping standards', 'A national database of patient information governance incidents', 'B', 'The NHS Data Security and Protection (DSP) Toolkit is an annual self-assessment framework that all NHS organisations and GP practices must complete to demonstrate compliance with UK GDPR, the Data Protection Act 2018, and the National Data Guardian''s 10 Data Security Standards. It is a key component of information governance within the broader clinical governance framework and is reviewed as part of CQC inspections.')
